WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.990 --> 00:00:02.970
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:09.430
-This is our third
of three panels.

00:00:09.430 --> 00:00:12.800
And this one is on
public discourse,

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:21.470
how news, cinema, advertising
gets out to the public

00:00:21.470 --> 00:00:26.460
and is shaped-- presumably to an
audience which is at least 50%

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:32.189
female-- and on the other
hand shaped mainly by men.

00:00:32.189 --> 00:00:38.320
So the panel consists of
Mary Mills, Liza Johnson,

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:40.470
and Christine Matthews
and is moderated

00:00:40.470 --> 00:00:42.650
by Kathleen Hall Jamieson.

00:00:42.650 --> 00:00:45.810
Kathleen is a professor
at the Annenberg School

00:00:45.810 --> 00:00:50.750
at the University
of Pennsylvania,

00:00:50.750 --> 00:00:55.390
author and co-author of 16 books
mostly on political discourse

00:00:55.390 --> 00:00:57.120
and politics.

00:00:57.120 --> 00:01:01.280
She's also a founder of
factcheck.org and more recently

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:04.019
sidecheck.org in 2015.

00:01:04.019 --> 00:01:07.280
And last night I
got to learn what

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:12.220
it's like to be an outsider at
a George Wallace rally, which

00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:13.060
was fascinating.

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:14.720
So I'll turn it
over to Kathleen.

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:16.130
-Thank you.

00:01:16.130 --> 00:01:16.850
Good afternoon.

00:01:16.850 --> 00:01:20.000
Welcome back.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.250
The premise of this panel
is that the popular culture,

00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:27.330
including politics, shapes the
way in which we see each other.

00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:29.500
And the talk in
those environments

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:32.510
and the visual images in
those environments matter.

00:01:32.510 --> 00:01:34.550
We're privileged to have
a panel today of people

00:01:34.550 --> 00:01:37.530
who are what I would call
custodians of that culture.

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:38.480
They understand it.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:39.540
They've worked within it.

00:01:39.540 --> 00:01:41.090
They felt the constraints of it.

00:01:41.090 --> 00:01:44.530
They are trying to break out
of it, many times successfully.

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:47.360
I'd like to frame our discussion
by going back to the 1950s

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:51.830
and situate us permanently there
for about a minute and a half.

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:53.860
In the 1950s, the
scholarly community

00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:58.280
recognized that televised
images over long periods of time

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:00.810
can cultivate our
view of reality,

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:02.859
that we can come
to see a world that

00:02:02.859 --> 00:02:04.650
is far different from
the world we actually

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:08.650
experience by experiencing
the world of televised images.

00:02:08.650 --> 00:02:10.720
And that body of
scholarship, produced largely

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:14.202
at the Annenberg School at the
University of Pennsylvania,

00:02:14.202 --> 00:02:15.660
said that, for
example, when you're

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:17.800
a very high consumer
of television,

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:20.820
you are far more likely to think
that the world is crime-ridden

00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:24.440
than it is and that your world
is crime-ridden than it is.

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:26.430
We replicated that
finding, finding

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:28.890
that when you watch high
amounts of local news,

00:02:28.890 --> 00:02:30.629
you think the same
thing, in addition,

00:02:30.629 --> 00:02:32.420
you're far more likely
to think that you're

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:34.600
going to be victim of a fire.

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:37.840
Now what that tells
us is ongoing exposure

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:40.130
to unquestioned
assumptions can ultimately

00:02:40.130 --> 00:02:43.470
shape the way in which we think
and the way in which we speak

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:45.870
and potentially the
ways in which we act.

00:02:45.870 --> 00:02:49.720
We also know from other research
that these kinds of images

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:53.940
can teach us how we should
function in situations.

00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:56.740
And sometimes that
can be negative.

00:02:56.740 --> 00:02:59.820
So, for example, you can
normalize perception of smoking

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:02.800
by having ongoing exposure of
both young men and young women

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.340
to people who are smoking in
video contexts, a finding we

00:03:06.340 --> 00:03:08.670
just replicated on YouTube.

00:03:08.670 --> 00:03:10.210
Well, we found
that when you look

00:03:10.210 --> 00:03:12.650
at an ongoing basis--
seeing a lot of people--

00:03:12.650 --> 00:03:15.200
and that is normative
in YouTube videos

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:17.780
about smoking-- a lot of
young people smoking often

00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:19.960
in their bedrooms, often
with their friends--

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:22.590
you are more likely to think
that other people smoke

00:03:22.590 --> 00:03:24.980
and your attitudes about
smoking are, as a result,

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:26.600
more likely to be positive.

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:29.970
So if we say that something as
basic as seeing other people

00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:32.600
doing things on an ongoing
basis can shape something

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:35.325
as potentially
damaging as increasing

00:03:35.325 --> 00:03:36.720
the likelihood of
smoking, you're

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:38.990
saying something which
is profoundly disturbing.

00:03:38.990 --> 00:03:41.660
But we also know
that images that you

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:44.300
see in this kind of
environment can help expand

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:46.830
your world in positive ways.

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:48.870
How many of us saw
a different world

00:03:48.870 --> 00:03:50.870
when we saw Julia
for the first time--

00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:52.630
if we are of a certain age?

00:03:52.630 --> 00:03:56.650
How many of us saw a
different kind of relationship

00:03:56.650 --> 00:03:58.650
when we saw Will &amp; Grace?

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:01.530
How many of us looked at
The Mary Tyler Moore Show

00:04:01.530 --> 00:04:04.560
and saw the struggles that
some of our generation

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:08.650
were experiencing as we
were entering the workforce?

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:11.250
Those kinds of portrayals
expand our sense

00:04:11.250 --> 00:04:12.510
of the available options.

00:04:12.510 --> 00:04:15.940
And as we watch fictive
characters dealing with them

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:18.890
either tell us what kinds of
things work or don't work,

00:04:18.890 --> 00:04:21.209
what might be
successful strategies

00:04:21.209 --> 00:04:22.730
or failed strategies.

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:24.890
In the process, of course,
it's possible to model

00:04:24.890 --> 00:04:28.140
a whole lot of dysfunction in
interpersonal relationships.

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:30.710
And as a result, we
can ask the question,

00:04:30.710 --> 00:04:34.300
what does it do when
people we care about

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:36.360
and the people we
are are portrayed

00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:38.230
in these kinds of venues?

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:41.910
I wrote a book in the mid-1990s
called Beyond the Double Bind--

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:43.120
Women in Leadership.

00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:45.510
It hypothesized that
historically women

00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:48.280
were placed in a situation in
which no matter what they did,

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:50.485
it was the wrong choice.

00:04:50.485 --> 00:04:52.880
And I called them
double binds and said

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:55.280
that what we've essentially
accomplished as women

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:58.370
across time and as people who
have been oppressed by others

00:04:58.370 --> 00:05:00.750
as a group across
time is found ways

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:03.900
to navigate out of those
socially constructed binds.

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.410
But we're still experiencing
the residue of them.

00:05:06.410 --> 00:05:09.160
So very early women
were told, you literally

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:12.090
can't go into the academy
because women's brains

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:14.970
can't work because their
uteruses are functioning.

00:05:14.970 --> 00:05:18.130
And so if your uterus is
functioning, your brain can't.

00:05:18.130 --> 00:05:19.780
The women who
overcame that came out

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:23.080
of the science curricula
inside women's colleges

00:05:23.080 --> 00:05:25.470
and they engaged in
experiments which showed,

00:05:25.470 --> 00:05:28.290
for example, that a menstruating
woman can add and subtract

00:05:28.290 --> 00:05:31.240
as well as a non-menstruating
woman, that a pregnant woman

00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:33.460
can multiply as well as
a non-pregnant woman,

00:05:33.460 --> 00:05:35.780
and interestingly enough,
she can do it just

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:38.850
as well as a man who is neither
menstruating nor pregnant.

00:05:38.850 --> 00:05:40.830
That's what you call
a control group.

00:05:40.830 --> 00:05:43.700
Now what is the residue?

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:46.010
The residue of that
is Donald Trump

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:49.120
suggesting that Megyn
Kelly is menstruating

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:51.740
when Megyn Kelly asks a
question about which Donald

00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:55.120
Trump disapproves about the
ways in which he's cast women.

00:05:55.120 --> 00:05:57.100
What it suggests
is that something

00:05:57.100 --> 00:05:59.240
is going wrong hormonally,
and as a result,

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:01.840
her brain isn't functioning
as well as it should.

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:04.530
And well, she's
bleeding from wherever.

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:07.960
And as Carly Fiorina notably
said in another context,

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:10.890
we all understood exactly
what he was saying.

00:06:10.890 --> 00:06:13.477
We also have a double bind
that I called silence shame.

00:06:13.477 --> 00:06:16.060
That is, women weren't allowed
to move into the public sphere,

00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:18.520
and if they did, they
were called whores.

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:21.350
As a result, women's
speech was substantially

00:06:21.350 --> 00:06:23.830
speech that was not heard
outside the limited sphere

00:06:23.830 --> 00:06:25.950
in which women were
able to operate.

00:06:25.950 --> 00:06:28.870
Well, we ultimately
overcame that historically.

00:06:28.870 --> 00:06:31.110
Many heroic women stood up.

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:33.170
Men of goodwill
stood up as well.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:35.930
And as a result, women moved
into the public sphere.

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:40.210
The residue of that
silent shame double bind

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:42.800
is one in which people say
Hillary Clinton is shouting.

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:45.280
It's not appropriate to shout.

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:48.180
When you pair that
with a man engaging

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:49.890
in exactly the
same decibel level,

00:06:49.890 --> 00:06:51.480
no one says that
man is shouting.

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:53.680
They say that man is forceful.

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:56.030
The residue of the double
bind is still being overcome.

00:06:56.030 --> 00:06:58.350
The argument of the book
was we overcome the residue

00:06:58.350 --> 00:07:01.120
by meta-communicating about it,
making people conscious of it.

00:07:01.120 --> 00:07:02.900
That's part of what
we're doing today

00:07:02.900 --> 00:07:04.690
as we move into all
of the other ways

00:07:04.690 --> 00:07:07.780
in which individuals are
marginalized by a society that

00:07:07.780 --> 00:07:10.950
needs help in reframing
its understanding of itself

00:07:10.950 --> 00:07:11.970
and of others.

00:07:11.970 --> 00:07:13.810
We saw it as well
with Hillary Clinton

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:16.580
when Hillary Clinton
pauses before she

00:07:16.580 --> 00:07:20.160
laughs when responding to a
question that is unanticipated.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:23.460
It was described as a cackle
by The New York Times.

00:07:23.460 --> 00:07:25.920
Rudy Giuliani, also a
front running candidate

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:27.750
during that
election, would pause

00:07:27.750 --> 00:07:30.380
before he would laugh in a way
that seemed a little eccentric

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:32.290
and no one called it a cackle.

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:35.250
We have a residue historically
of the ways in which we've

00:07:35.250 --> 00:07:38.040
marginalized female speech
in the form of a vocabulary

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:39.580
to condemn women's discourse.

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:41.430
And there's no
comparable vocabulary

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:44.520
to condemn or even to
describe exactly the same kind

00:07:44.520 --> 00:07:46.267
of behavior when
we find it in male.

00:07:46.267 --> 00:07:48.100
Finally, there was a
third bind-- I actually

00:07:48.100 --> 00:07:50.308
looked at five; I'm only
going to [INAUDIBLE] three--

00:07:50.308 --> 00:07:52.260
called aging invisibility.

00:07:52.260 --> 00:07:55.260
Women were led into
positions marginalized out

00:07:55.260 --> 00:07:57.070
during the childbearing
years and then told

00:07:57.070 --> 00:07:59.278
that they were too old just
as they were about to hit

00:07:59.278 --> 00:08:00.890
their professional stride.

00:08:00.890 --> 00:08:03.920
I call that aging invisibility.

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:06.450
Aging invisibility is
ultimately overcome

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:09.290
as women move into leadership
positions around the world--

00:08:09.290 --> 00:08:11.350
Margaret Thatcher,
Indira Gandhi.

00:08:11.350 --> 00:08:14.120
We move onto our Supreme
Court-- Sandra Day O'Connor

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:15.240
taking a lead there.

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:17.910
Women move into secretary
of state positions.

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:21.770
And what's ultimately the
residue that is still there?

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:24.320
You have a conservative
talk radio host who says,

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:26.690
do we really want to
watch Hillary Clinton get

00:08:26.690 --> 00:08:28.320
old in front of
our eyes as she's

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:30.070
president of the United States?

00:08:30.070 --> 00:08:32.120
My answer is, I'd
like to see that.

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:37.919
And with that, as
a transition, it

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:40.740
is my pleasure to introduce
our first panelist.

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:42.830
Mary Mills is the
Worldwide Director

00:08:42.830 --> 00:08:44.250
of Strategic Intelligence.

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:46.500
Now, labeling matters.

00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:48.910
Think about this label
for just a moment.

00:08:48.910 --> 00:08:53.660
The Worldwide Director of
Strategic Intelligence,

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:58.340
is that not a powerful label?

00:08:58.340 --> 00:08:59.050
My pleasure.

00:08:59.050 --> 00:09:00.894
Mary, to turn the
panel over to you.

00:09:00.894 --> 00:09:02.860
Thanks, Kathleen.

00:09:02.860 --> 00:09:05.550
"Gender Fluidity
in Advertising."

00:09:05.550 --> 00:09:07.730
I need to qualify that.

00:09:07.730 --> 00:09:10.160
It's actually more appropriately
given this context,

00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:13.480
it should be entitled
toward gender fluidity

00:09:13.480 --> 00:09:15.990
in advertising because
it's a big claim.

00:09:15.990 --> 00:09:17.270
And it's an optimistic one.

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:19.260
And it's picking up right
where Kathleen led us

00:09:19.260 --> 00:09:21.390
in terms of the
positive influence

00:09:21.390 --> 00:09:22.630
that advertising can have.

00:09:22.630 --> 00:09:25.110
And that's what I want to
talk to you about today.

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:27.400
I'm going to show you some
examples of advertising

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:30.390
using men and women in
respectful and disrespectful

00:09:30.390 --> 00:09:31.480
ways.

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:33.660
Some of it is our own work
from Saatchi &amp; Saatchi.

00:09:33.660 --> 00:09:35.690
Some of it is from
other agencies.

00:09:35.690 --> 00:09:38.700
But I want to show you
how it mirrors who we are

00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:41.110
and how we can use
it for better good.

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:44.730
First, a context.

00:09:44.730 --> 00:09:47.670
So three things I need you
to understand about this.

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:50.590
When we say language in my
business in the advertising

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:53.280
game, it's words and pictures.

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:55.480
I want to talk about that
in a little more detail.

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:59.510
I want to talk about how we can
use advertising in a better way

00:09:59.510 --> 00:10:01.200
that you might not
have anticipated.

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:03.780
As one of my kids
has on her bulletin

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:07.750
board on her desk, a
little poster that said,

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:10.140
if you talk to people the
way that advertising does,

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:12.900
they would punch
you in the face.

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:16.970
So that's my home life.

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:19.530
And my kids remind me
constantly that advertising

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:20.890
is an interruption.

00:10:20.890 --> 00:10:22.440
It's not warranted.

00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:24.220
It's not liked.

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:25.560
It messes up our lives.

00:10:25.560 --> 00:10:29.180
And my agenda here is to shift
your perception of advertising,

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:32.330
that, in fact, it can do
some really decent things.

00:10:32.330 --> 00:10:35.210
So first and foremost,
we talk about language.

00:10:35.210 --> 00:10:36.480
It's words and pictures.

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:38.162
Words are just
part of the story.

00:10:38.162 --> 00:10:40.370
And I don't even want to
put a number on whether it's

00:10:40.370 --> 00:10:42.470
half or a quarter or a third.

00:10:42.470 --> 00:10:45.770
It's two very different ways
of communicating messaging.

00:10:45.770 --> 00:10:46.700
Just the way this is.

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:47.360
One is art.

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:49.070
And one says, "This is art."

00:10:49.070 --> 00:10:50.560
They do two very different jobs.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:52.870
We have two very different
jobs within the agency

00:10:52.870 --> 00:10:56.010
as art director and writer,
but they work together

00:10:56.010 --> 00:10:56.934
on everything.

00:10:56.934 --> 00:10:58.350
So even an art
director and writer

00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:00.100
would work on a radio script.

00:11:00.100 --> 00:11:02.000
They would work on a
print ad, whether or not

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.500
there is any art
direction involved.

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:06.400
It's two ways of
thinking of things, two

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:09.570
ways of getting the idea right.

00:11:09.570 --> 00:11:13.150
Public discourse-- how
do I fit into this panel

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:17.300
here in terms of how we
affect views and beliefs

00:11:17.300 --> 00:11:18.950
in the public discourse?

00:11:18.950 --> 00:11:22.170
Broadly, historically,
movies would be considered

00:11:22.170 --> 00:11:25.320
entertainment and escape.

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:28.790
Speeches are about
visions, common rhetoric,

00:11:28.790 --> 00:11:31.620
inspiring people to take
action at a certain time.

00:11:31.620 --> 00:11:34.660
And ads are about us
selling you stuff.

00:11:34.660 --> 00:11:37.260
So it seems like we're the
poor cousin on all this.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:39.290
But what I want to talk
to you about is, given

00:11:39.290 --> 00:11:41.110
the proliferation
of advertising,

00:11:41.110 --> 00:11:42.870
the amount of
money that's spent,

00:11:42.870 --> 00:11:45.730
the ubiquity of advertising,
and the global sharing

00:11:45.730 --> 00:11:49.560
of advertising, it has a
power that we're just starting

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:53.370
to realize and tap into.

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:56.040
Finally, one of the things
that I think advertising can do

00:11:56.040 --> 00:11:57.150
