00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:02.490
women office holders.

00:35:02.490 --> 00:35:05.990
First, let's just take a
look at the lay of the land.

00:35:05.990 --> 00:35:08.570
This is something I know
intuitively but not everybody

00:35:08.570 --> 00:35:10.760
in the room may know, which
is women are obviously

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:12.940
very under-represented.

00:35:12.940 --> 00:35:18.210
They're 19% of Congress, roughly
25% statewide office holders

00:35:18.210 --> 00:35:23.820
or in the state legislature,
yet they are 53% of all voters.

00:35:23.820 --> 00:35:27.420
There are particularly few
Republican women in Congress.

00:35:27.420 --> 00:35:31.280
So you can see-- and this
data comes from the Center

00:35:31.280 --> 00:35:33.620
for American Women in
Politics out of Rutgers,

00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:37.150
which is a wonderful, valuable
source of information on all

00:35:37.150 --> 00:35:39.360
this kind of information.

00:35:39.360 --> 00:35:42.570
So we've got 62 Democratic
women in the House,

00:35:42.570 --> 00:35:47.390
22 Republican women, 14
Democratic women US senators

00:35:47.390 --> 00:35:48.910
and six Republican women.

00:35:48.910 --> 00:35:51.220
So there's lots of
reasons-- including

00:35:51.220 --> 00:35:55.710
the pipeline, funding-- for
the lack of Republican Women.

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:57.450
One of the other
reasons is they just

00:35:57.450 --> 00:36:00.420
have a really difficult time
getting out of primaries.

00:36:00.420 --> 00:36:04.050
And they're about 20 points
less likely to get out

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:06.230
of their primary than
a Democratic woman is

00:36:06.230 --> 00:36:07.790
to get out of her primary.

00:36:07.790 --> 00:36:10.630
One thing is true, Republican
primary electorates

00:36:10.630 --> 00:36:12.020
are majority male.

00:36:12.020 --> 00:36:15.350
Democratic primary electorates
tend to be majority female.

00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:17.310
That may have one
thing to do with it.

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:21.800
But in 2012, for example,
57% of Republican women

00:36:21.800 --> 00:36:26.410
lost their primaries compared
to 38% of Democratic women.

00:36:26.410 --> 00:36:29.640
In 2014, it was slightly better,
but Republican women, again,

00:36:29.640 --> 00:36:32.550
were 20 points less likely to
come out of their primaries.

00:36:32.550 --> 00:36:38.240
So we're getting
clogged up there.

00:36:38.240 --> 00:36:40.700
There are many reasons for
this lack of political parity.

00:36:40.700 --> 00:36:43.200
One thing that we're
obviously examining today

00:36:43.200 --> 00:36:47.390
is how language
plays a role in it.

00:36:47.390 --> 00:36:50.600
So one thing I want to talk
about is what's in a name.

00:36:50.600 --> 00:36:56.290
And thinking back to 2008,
both Hillary Clinton and Barack

00:36:56.290 --> 00:36:59.270
Obama were US senators when
they ran for president.

00:36:59.270 --> 00:37:05.680
But a study found that Senator
Clinton was four times as

00:37:05.680 --> 00:37:09.490
likely to be called by her first
name than was Senator Obama.

00:37:09.490 --> 00:37:13.220
So her title was dropped
and she was just referred to

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:15.120
as Hillary or Hillary Clinton.

00:37:15.120 --> 00:37:17.170
Male anchors, male
reporters were

00:37:17.170 --> 00:37:20.170
more likely than female
anchors or female broadcasters

00:37:20.170 --> 00:37:21.470
to drop her title.

00:37:21.470 --> 00:37:25.070
So I really like that
Kathleen emphasized the title.

00:37:25.070 --> 00:37:30.140
Because what happens
is titles infer status.

00:37:30.140 --> 00:37:31.430
They infer power.

00:37:31.430 --> 00:37:33.820
And for women candidates,
that title gets dropped.

00:37:37.770 --> 00:37:40.320
I've done a lot of focus
groups, a lot of research.

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:42.780
One thing that I learned from
doing focus group with swing

00:37:42.780 --> 00:37:47.600
women-- we were imagining
a different scenario,

00:37:47.600 --> 00:37:50.110
but a debate where
you had Hillary

00:37:50.110 --> 00:37:53.210
Clinton as a Democratic nominee
and a Republican nominee.

00:37:53.210 --> 00:37:57.130
And we asked, what
would be the best way

00:37:57.130 --> 00:37:58.480
to refer to Hillary Clinton?

00:37:58.480 --> 00:38:00.350
What if somebody
called her Hillary?

00:38:00.350 --> 00:38:02.260
And the women didn't
like it at all.

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:05.000
They felt absolutely
she should be referred

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:08.090
to as Secretary Clinton.

00:38:08.090 --> 00:38:09.800
I haven't watched the
Democratic debates.

00:38:09.800 --> 00:38:10.530
I've seen clips.

00:38:10.530 --> 00:38:12.640
I think that's how
Bernie Sanders refers

00:38:12.640 --> 00:38:14.760
to her, as Secretary Clinton.

00:38:14.760 --> 00:38:19.700
So either that's
second nature or he's

00:38:19.700 --> 00:38:22.000
also seen some data
that says this is really

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:23.930
what you need to do.

00:38:23.930 --> 00:38:28.550
Back in 2014, we were involved
in pretty much every US Senate

00:38:28.550 --> 00:38:30.440
race where there was
a woman candidate

00:38:30.440 --> 00:38:33.080
either on the Republican
side or the Democratic side.

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:35.540
So in North Carolina,
speaker of the house

00:38:35.540 --> 00:38:39.530
Thom Tillis was running against
the incumbent US Senator Kay

00:38:39.530 --> 00:38:40.520
Hagan.

00:38:40.520 --> 00:38:44.480
And in a debate, she referred
to him as Speaker Tillis.

00:38:44.480 --> 00:38:46.360
He called her Kay.

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:49.300
And there was a big backlash.

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:55.310
And his point was I would
prefer that you call me Thom.

00:38:55.310 --> 00:38:57.930
If you were Bob Hagan, I
would've called you Bob.

00:38:57.930 --> 00:38:59.600
But it was just unseemly.

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:03.690
And there was a backlash
and seen as disrespectful

00:39:03.690 --> 00:39:05.450
that he called her Kay.

00:39:05.450 --> 00:39:08.440
And you can see, again,
candidates may brand themselves

00:39:08.440 --> 00:39:09.610
using their first name.

00:39:09.610 --> 00:39:10.900
Carly for President.

00:39:10.900 --> 00:39:12.130
Jeb!

00:39:12.130 --> 00:39:13.350
2016.

00:39:13.350 --> 00:39:16.150
But that's something
you have to do.

00:39:16.150 --> 00:39:18.440
Particularly, if you're a
man running against a woman,

00:39:18.440 --> 00:39:21.210
you should never refer
to her by her first name.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:24.560
You should always
include the title.

00:39:24.560 --> 00:39:26.130
This is a really
interesting study.

00:39:26.130 --> 00:39:30.162
Speaking of titles
and associations,

00:39:30.162 --> 00:39:34.300
a new study out of Vanderbilt
done by an assistant professor

00:39:34.300 --> 00:39:35.910
of political science there.

00:39:35.910 --> 00:39:37.410
And this was done in Florida.

00:39:37.410 --> 00:39:40.920
They had a random
sample of respondents.

00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:43.020
And they showed these
images of men and women

00:39:43.020 --> 00:39:44.910
in professional attire.

00:39:44.910 --> 00:39:51.910
And what happened was the words
most associated with the men

00:39:51.910 --> 00:39:55.650
were president and
executive and for the women

00:39:55.650 --> 00:39:59.010
it was assistant or aide.

00:39:59.010 --> 00:40:02.680
And she found that
regardless of some--

00:40:02.680 --> 00:40:06.220
she had done some prescreening
questions about likelihood

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:07.850
to vote for a woman candidate.

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:11.550
Even among those who said,
yeah, I'm very open, absolutely

00:40:11.550 --> 00:40:15.530
ready and likely to vote
for a woman candidate--

00:40:15.530 --> 00:40:18.370
if they were more likely to
associate words like assistant

00:40:18.370 --> 00:40:21.000
or aide to the woman
rather than the man,

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:23.210
it had an impact on
their vote behavior.

00:40:23.210 --> 00:40:25.300
So this is a form
of hidden bias.

00:40:25.300 --> 00:40:26.770
I've had women
members of Congress

00:40:26.770 --> 00:40:29.380
tell me they've
had instances where

00:40:29.380 --> 00:40:31.240
they've gotten into
the member elevator

00:40:31.240 --> 00:40:34.190
and they've been told to get
out because they're staff.

00:40:34.190 --> 00:40:37.410
Or they've been on
the floor of Congress

00:40:37.410 --> 00:40:39.160
and have been
instructed to leave

00:40:39.160 --> 00:40:40.910
because staff's not allowed.

00:40:40.910 --> 00:40:45.160
So there's a lot of hidden bias.

00:40:45.160 --> 00:40:50.660
And I think it's important
to recognize that.

00:40:50.660 --> 00:40:53.670
So of course we have to
have some Donald Trump-isms.

00:40:53.670 --> 00:40:57.490
This is actually rather mild
compared to many of the things

00:40:57.490 --> 00:40:58.510
Donald Trump says.

00:40:58.510 --> 00:41:03.190
But clearly he really
cannot handle smart women.

00:41:03.190 --> 00:41:06.000
And so this was a tweet.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.280
He loves to be on the Twitter.

00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:10.900
And he said, "I just
realized that if you listen

00:41:10.900 --> 00:41:13.540
to Carly Fiorina for more
than 10 minutes straight,

00:41:13.540 --> 00:41:15.220
you develop a massive headache.

00:41:15.220 --> 00:41:16.230
She has zero chance!"

00:41:16.230 --> 00:41:20.050
So what he's saying is her voice
is irritating, it's grating.

00:41:20.050 --> 00:41:23.430
He said the exact same thing
about Hillary Clinton's voice,

00:41:23.430 --> 00:41:26.700
that it gave him a headache.
"She's so theatrical.

00:41:26.700 --> 00:41:30.020
And her voice just
gives me a headache."

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:32.570
So the one thing Donald
Trump did tell The New York

00:41:32.570 --> 00:41:34.860
Times that he wouldn't
say about Carly Fiorina

00:41:34.860 --> 00:41:37.490
is he did say he would
not call her honey.

00:41:37.490 --> 00:41:38.757
So you got that.

00:41:41.732 --> 00:41:43.510
This is one of
those things where

00:41:43.510 --> 00:41:47.630
women's voices are discussed.

00:41:47.630 --> 00:41:50.320
They become something
that is other.

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:52.880
And the journalist Bob
Woodward, for example,

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:56.000
criticized Hillary Clinton
for shouting too much.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:58.560
He said there's something
very unrelaxed about the way

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:01.840
she communicates, and that
she's not doing better

00:42:01.840 --> 00:42:03.270
because she shouts too much.

00:42:03.270 --> 00:42:05.559
And again, Kathleen, I
think you addressed that.

00:42:05.559 --> 00:42:07.100
In fact, I'll have
a couple of points

00:42:07.100 --> 00:42:09.670
that you addressed,
that a woman has

00:42:09.670 --> 00:42:13.810
a very narrow bandwidth
in which you're

00:42:13.810 --> 00:42:15.790
able to talk and project.

00:42:15.790 --> 00:42:19.260
And if you think about it,
you're at a gigantic rally.

00:42:19.260 --> 00:42:21.990
You're going to have to
raise your voice, right?

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:25.740
As opposed to speaking to
a small group of people.

00:42:25.740 --> 00:42:28.980
Again, so women are
criticized for their voices.

00:42:28.980 --> 00:42:31.620
They give people headaches
or they're too screechy

00:42:31.620 --> 00:42:33.940
or they're too loud.

00:42:33.940 --> 00:42:35.560
And this was the iconic moment.

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:37.600
This really was.

00:42:37.600 --> 00:42:39.580
And Kathleen, again,
referred to it.

00:42:39.580 --> 00:42:43.410
I think this was Carly Fiorina's
best moment of the campaign.

00:42:43.410 --> 00:42:46.160
So she was asked about Donald
Trump in Rolling Stone who

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:47.550
said, "Look at that face.

00:42:47.550 --> 00:42:48.870
Would anybody vote for that?

00:42:48.870 --> 00:42:52.050
Can you imagine that, the
face of our next president?"

00:42:52.050 --> 00:42:57.180
And so he tried to pretend that
he was meaning-- I don't even

00:42:57.180 --> 00:43:01.230
know what you could
possibly mean by that--

00:43:01.230 --> 00:43:03.730
but he was trying to
pretend it was her persona.

00:43:03.730 --> 00:43:08.116
So Jake Tapper
asked Ms. Fiorina,

00:43:08.116 --> 00:43:09.240
how do you feel about that?

00:43:09.240 --> 00:43:13.050
And she said, I think women all
over this country heard very

00:43:13.050 --> 00:43:15.370
clearly what Mr. Trump said.

00:43:15.370 --> 00:43:18.840
And then she dropped the
mic, because it was great.

00:43:18.840 --> 00:43:20.680
And it was really the
only time I have ever

00:43:20.680 --> 00:43:23.530
seen shame or embarrassment
on Donald Trump's face.

00:43:23.530 --> 00:43:25.690
Really, he did blush a little.

00:43:25.690 --> 00:43:27.230
And then he
stammered, oh, I think

00:43:27.230 --> 00:43:30.040
she has a beautiful face,
because he doesn't even

00:43:30.040 --> 00:43:32.410
know what to say.

00:43:32.410 --> 00:43:35.200
So that gets to the
attractiveness predicament.

00:43:35.200 --> 00:43:38.580
And I think Kathleen has
obviously written books.

00:43:38.580 --> 00:43:40.920
It's the double bind.

00:43:40.920 --> 00:43:43.105
But the attractiveness
predicament

00:43:43.105 --> 00:43:44.830
is a really big issue.

00:43:44.830 --> 00:43:47.750
So we did a ton of focus
groups, a ton of research

00:43:47.750 --> 00:43:51.770
around the US Senate
races in 2014.

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:54.060
And as I said, we were
involved in almost every one

00:43:54.060 --> 00:43:56.930
that had a woman candidate
on either side of the aisle.

00:43:56.930 --> 00:44:00.470
So in this case, this
was really unfortunate,

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:03.810
and we were kind of horrified.

00:44:03.810 --> 00:44:07.840
Party spokesperson called
the US Senate candidate

00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:12.790
from Kentucky "an empty dress
who babbles incoherently."

00:44:12.790 --> 00:44:15.780
So can you ever imagine
it being said about a man

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:17.070
that he babbles incoherently?

00:44:20.096 --> 00:44:21.810
No.

00:44:21.810 --> 00:44:23.680
What's interesting,
though, is appearance

00:44:23.680 --> 00:44:27.220
is not only a point of
discussion, observation,

00:44:27.220 --> 00:44:29.930
criticism for men
of women candidates,

00:44:29.930 --> 00:44:33.340
women also criticize other
women based on appearance.

00:44:33.340 --> 00:44:36.180
It has to do with relatability.

00:44:36.180 --> 00:44:38.570
In Georgia, for example,
I did focus groups.

00:44:38.570 --> 00:44:40.720
And you may recall
that Michelle Nunn

00:44:40.720 --> 00:44:43.750
was a candidate for US Senate.

00:44:43.750 --> 00:44:48.750
She's smart, accomplished,
seems like a wonderful person.

00:44:48.750 --> 00:44:50.830
Some of the comments
in the focus groups,

00:44:50.830 --> 00:44:54.740
though, were-- she looks
like-- and you guys will

00:44:54.740 --> 00:44:58.000
find this ironic--
a liberal college

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:01.540
professor from the Northeast.

00:45:01.540 --> 00:45:05.590
So what they were saying
is she's not ratable to us

00:45:05.590 --> 00:45:06.430
here in Georgia.

00:45:06.430 --> 00:45:08.050
I can't relate to her.

00:45:08.050 --> 00:45:09.140
She's other.

00:45:09.140 --> 00:45:10.120
She's different.

00:45:10.120 --> 00:45:11.950
I don't know.

00:45:11.950 --> 00:45:16.780
In Louisiana, we were
doing focus groups.

00:45:16.780 --> 00:45:20.830
And one of the participants--
who I did not enjoy at all--

00:45:20.830 --> 00:45:23.950
said about the incoming
US senator, wow,

00:45:23.950 --> 00:45:26.880
she's really gotten old and fat.

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:31.010
And he, of course, was old
and fat, but never mind.

00:45:31.010 --> 00:45:34.270
And he just said it like it was
some kind of great indictment

00:45:34.270 --> 00:45:37.010
and great insight on his part.

00:45:37.010 --> 00:45:39.717
So that was just
really annoying.

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:45.940
So there's how we look,
there's how we talk, oh,

00:45:45.940 --> 00:45:47.020
and how we laugh.

00:45:47.020 --> 00:45:49.530
So we are supposed to smile,
but we're not supposed

00:45:49.530 --> 00:45:52.247
to laugh too big or too loud.

00:45:52.247 --> 00:45:53.705
This was a comment
on social media.

00:45:53.705 --> 00:45:56.190
"Hillary's cackle alone
is enough to keep her

00:45:56.190 --> 00:45:59.160
off the world stage."

00:45:59.160 --> 00:46:03.690
So cackle is something
a witch does, right?

00:46:03.690 --> 00:46:05.950
And a witch rhymes with-- right?

00:46:05.950 --> 00:46:10.180
And can you imagine a US
president who cackles?

00:46:10.180 --> 00:46:13.150
No, I think that is actually
one of the most damaging words--

00:46:13.150 --> 00:46:15.680
cackle.

00:46:15.680 --> 00:46:17.260
I did a little Google search.

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:21.820
Lots of YouTube videos, mix-ups
of Hillary Clinton's cackle.

00:46:21.820 --> 00:46:24.970
And I think that's
actually very damaging.

00:46:24.970 --> 00:46:29.150
So then, of course,
women have to be smart,

00:46:29.150 --> 00:46:31.250
but they also have
to be likable.

00:46:31.250 --> 00:46:35.257
So they have to be smart.

00:46:35.257 --> 00:46:36.340
They have to be competent.

00:46:36.340 --> 00:46:38.950
They have to be not
too this, not too that.

00:46:38.950 --> 00:46:42.960
And this as important to
women as it is to men.

00:46:42.960 --> 00:46:46.690
So this is a quote
from a big donor

00:46:46.690 --> 00:46:48.720
who had given to Barack Obama.

00:46:48.720 --> 00:46:51.230
"It's not that I don't
think she's competent."

00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:53.230
This is about Hillary
Clinton. "She's competent.

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:55.370
She's just hard to like."

00:46:55.370 --> 00:46:58.450
So this is somebody
who's saying why

00:46:58.450 --> 00:47:00.900
he's withholding making
a donation to Hillary

00:47:00.900 --> 00:47:04.930
Clinton when he supported
Barack Obama in 2008 and 2012.

00:47:04.930 --> 00:47:08.092
"She's just not likable."

00:47:08.092 --> 00:47:09.800
And this is about
Carly Fiorina, and this

00:47:09.800 --> 00:47:11.430
is a woman saying it actually.

00:47:11.430 --> 00:47:13.540
And the thing
about Carly Fiorina

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:16.360
is I really think she
overperformed in the debates.

00:47:16.360 --> 00:47:19.380
Her command of facts and her
ability to talk policy, I think

00:47:19.380 --> 00:47:20.830
was really impressive.

00:47:20.830 --> 00:47:24.960
So then she was criticized
for not smiling enough.

00:47:24.960 --> 00:47:27.170
So she had to really
work on relatability.

00:47:27.170 --> 00:47:29.500
And this was a woman saying
there's a hardness in how

00:47:29.500 --> 00:47:32.030
she speaks and carries herself.

00:47:32.030 --> 00:47:34.390
Social media can be brutal.

00:47:34.390 --> 00:47:38.170
The words are OK, but look at
this image of Carly Fiorina

00:47:38.170 --> 00:47:40.630
as a little girl in
pink running a company.

00:47:40.630 --> 00:47:44.710
And the Democratic National
Committee did this.

00:47:44.710 --> 00:47:46.910
On social media, it
can be very brutal.

00:47:46.910 --> 00:47:48.576
Hashtag,
#wordsthatdon'tdescribeHillary.

00:47:50.540 --> 00:47:54.400
An analysis of 12,000 tweets
was done by two PhD students.

00:47:54.400 --> 00:47:56.980
1 in 12 comments was
about her appearance.

00:47:56.980 --> 00:47:59.350
For men, in a sexual
way, and for women,

00:47:59.350 --> 00:48:01.940
about likability
and relatability.

00:48:01.940 --> 00:48:04.330
Traditional media
isn't perfect either.

00:48:04.330 --> 00:48:06.940
A reporter told me that
the original headline

00:48:06.940 --> 00:48:10.500
read "Gloria Steinem and
Madeline Albright Scold Young

00:48:10.500 --> 00:48:12.715
Women Backing Bernie Sanders."

00:48:12.715 --> 00:48:13.840
They got a little backlash.

00:48:13.840 --> 00:48:15.760
They changed it to "rebuke."

00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:18.950
Now scold is a word-- you may be
familiar with the Women's Media

00:48:18.950 --> 00:48:19.450
Center.

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:20.908
They have something
called Name It.

00:48:20.908 --> 00:48:21.560
Change It.

00:48:21.560 --> 00:48:24.030
And they had a glossary
of words that they

00:48:24.030 --> 00:48:26.580
recommended the media not
use because they were sexist.

00:48:26.580 --> 00:48:29.204
Scold was one of them.

00:48:29.204 --> 00:48:31.620
I don't know if you've heard
of the Hillary Rodham Clinton

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:32.800
super-volunteers.

00:48:32.800 --> 00:48:34.960
These are words that
they have decided

00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:38.730
are sexist surrounding
Hillary Clinton.

00:48:38.730 --> 00:48:40.640
I think this goes
a little too far.

00:48:40.640 --> 00:48:42.480
I think it's a good
point of discussion.

00:48:42.480 --> 00:48:45.330
I think out of-- well,
it says "our of touch"--

00:48:45.330 --> 00:48:48.130
but out of touch,
represents the past,

00:48:48.130 --> 00:48:52.480
I don't see that as overly
sexist, but they do.

00:48:52.480 --> 00:48:53.930
And they say they're watching.

00:48:53.930 --> 00:48:57.970
Finally, just to wrap
up, I have done some work

00:48:57.970 --> 00:48:59.330
with this great project.

00:48:59.330 --> 00:49:04.195
It's a collaboration,
a nonpartisan project

00:49:04.195 --> 00:49:06.820
of the Center for American Women
in Politics in the Barbara Lee

00:49:06.820 --> 00:49:10.030
Family Foundation to
track, analyze, eliminate

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:12.660
gender dynamics in the
2016 presidential election.

00:49:12.660 --> 00:49:15.600
So not that they'll
have anything to do,

00:49:15.600 --> 00:49:19.100
but you can find them on
Facebook and on Twitter

00:49:19.100 --> 00:49:20.720
under Gender Watch 2016.

00:49:20.720 --> 00:49:22.770
And I highly recommend them.

00:49:22.770 --> 00:49:24.507
They've written some
interesting things.

00:49:24.507 --> 00:49:25.840
I've done some things with them.

00:49:25.840 --> 00:49:29.841
And they're calling it
out, which is fascinating.

00:49:29.841 --> 00:49:30.340
-Thank you.

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:32.268
[APPLAUSE]

00:49:40.944 --> 00:49:43.420
Mary, they've spent
billions of dollars.

00:49:43.420 --> 00:49:45.950
These are incredibly
talented people.

00:49:45.950 --> 00:49:47.810
They have all the
research in the world.

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:50.790
They charge their clients
a whole lot of money.

00:49:50.790 --> 00:49:54.430
Why did it take them so long
to get any of this right?

00:49:54.430 --> 00:49:55.690
-It's hard.

00:49:55.690 --> 00:49:57.430
First and foremost,
it's too easy

00:49:57.430 --> 00:50:03.020
to either blame our clients or
blame that most of the writers

00:50:03.020 --> 00:50:06.140
and the actors in the
early days were men.

00:50:06.140 --> 00:50:09.650
It comes back to the
point of listening.

00:50:09.650 --> 00:50:13.680
I am not the woman that we
target more often than not.

00:50:13.680 --> 00:50:16.240
All my assumptions and
biases when I walk into work

00:50:16.240 --> 00:50:19.190
and I write a brief or I
train a group or I teach them,

00:50:19.190 --> 00:50:20.380
I have to put them in check.

00:50:20.380 --> 00:50:21.769
It's really hard to do.

00:50:21.769 --> 00:50:24.060
Most clients look at the work
that we do, and go, yeah,

00:50:24.060 --> 00:50:25.220
my wife would love that.

00:50:25.220 --> 00:50:27.100
That's a great ad.

00:50:27.100 --> 00:50:28.580
Stop that behavior.

00:50:28.580 --> 00:50:30.400
It's such ingrained
human behavior.

00:50:30.400 --> 00:50:32.470
But if we listen, if we
ask the right questions,

00:50:32.470 --> 00:50:35.840
and truly, truly engage the
audience with whom we'd like

00:50:35.840 --> 00:50:38.790
to communicate, magic happens.

00:50:38.790 --> 00:50:40.804
It's just obviously we
don't do it often enough.

00:50:40.804 --> 00:50:41.345
It's too bad.

00:50:41.345 --> 00:50:43.190
Actually, North America,
we're not great at it.

00:50:43.190 --> 00:50:44.510
We're better at it in the UK.

00:50:44.510 --> 00:50:46.700
We're better at it in Asia.

00:50:46.700 --> 00:50:48.880
Intuitively, they seem
to understand-- I mean,

00:50:48.880 --> 00:50:50.890
those are the guys
that did the gorilla.

00:50:50.890 --> 00:50:52.300
They understand guys.

00:50:52.300 --> 00:50:54.820
They didn't have to do
focus groups for it.

00:50:54.820 --> 00:50:56.995
We're getting better,
but yeah, it's shocking.

00:50:56.995 --> 00:50:59.620
I think now that we have data to
show how much money is wasted,

00:50:59.620 --> 00:51:02.091
they may pay attention to that.

00:51:02.091 --> 00:51:05.041
-Please tell us who you are
and frame your question.

00:51:05.041 --> 00:51:05.540
-Hi.

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:06.960
My name is Globiana.

00:51:06.960 --> 00:51:09.050
I'm a writer.

00:51:09.050 --> 00:51:10.750
It's interesting to
me now that you're

00:51:10.750 --> 00:51:14.940
talking about what's not said.

00:51:14.940 --> 00:51:17.950
I wrote down a
whole list of words

00:51:17.950 --> 00:51:23.470
that I heard in
conjunction with images

00:51:23.470 --> 00:51:27.420
that I see in news, either in
print or with the voiceover.

00:51:27.420 --> 00:51:28.850
It doesn't really matter.

00:51:28.850 --> 00:51:31.470
And so I see pictures of
large groups of people,

00:51:31.470 --> 00:51:35.480
insurrectionists they're called,
peacekeepers, demonstrators,

00:51:35.480 --> 00:51:39.680
sunis, climate change experts,
rebels, world leaders, pirates,

00:51:39.680 --> 00:51:45.740
Iraqis, and it goes on.

00:51:45.740 --> 00:51:48.470
When I look at the picture,
phenotypically what I see

00:51:48.470 --> 00:51:49.970
is men.

00:51:49.970 --> 00:51:54.700
That's the one word that I never
hear is they're not called men.

00:51:54.700 --> 00:51:59.730
When women are involved-- oh,
yes, remember Arab Spring?

00:51:59.730 --> 00:52:03.760
There were women, and boy,
did they make a point of that.

00:52:03.760 --> 00:52:08.986
Of course, the Democratic
primaries, we had the LPGA.

00:52:08.986 --> 00:52:11.110
-And to whom would you like
to phrase the question?

00:52:11.110 --> 00:52:12.890
-The question is-- I don't care.

00:52:12.890 --> 00:52:14.090
It's just that it scares me.

00:52:14.090 --> 00:52:16.280
And I want to know
if you people have

00:52:16.280 --> 00:52:17.885
any sense of what's going on.

00:52:22.730 --> 00:52:24.500
Why is this happening, I guess?

00:52:24.500 --> 00:52:27.670
It scares me.

00:52:27.670 --> 00:52:29.020
-Do you see it as happening?

00:52:29.020 --> 00:52:30.750
And if so, why?

00:52:30.750 --> 00:52:31.460
-Good question.

00:52:34.045 --> 00:52:35.420
-Just on the whole
pronoun thing,

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:39.092
what is the "it" that is said
to be happening, perhaps,

00:52:39.092 --> 00:52:39.800
may be happening?

00:52:39.800 --> 00:52:40.070
-I'm not sure I understand.

00:52:40.070 --> 00:52:41.910
-Leaving out the word men.

00:52:41.910 --> 00:52:45.300
Refusing to say the word
men when what we see is men.

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:47.540
-I don't know if this really
addresses your question,

00:52:47.540 --> 00:52:52.670
but as a person who
does a job who is also

00:52:52.670 --> 00:52:54.941
a woman, every time I am
in public, people say,

00:52:54.941 --> 00:52:56.690
oh, what's it like to
be a woman director?

00:52:56.690 --> 00:52:59.167
And I often think what
it would be like-- I even

00:52:59.167 --> 00:53:01.250
have a plan that I would
like to do this with some

00:53:01.250 --> 00:53:04.230
of my male colleagues some
time that we can all do press

00:53:04.230 --> 00:53:06.380
together so that they
can ask those guys like,

00:53:06.380 --> 00:53:08.720
so how is it being
a man director?

00:53:08.720 --> 00:53:13.160
And I do think that the
legion of the unmarked terms

00:53:13.160 --> 00:53:18.150
of masculinity is
systematically present because

00:53:18.150 --> 00:53:19.870
of the patriarchy.

00:53:19.870 --> 00:53:24.240
And I think that is
true and that we just

00:53:24.240 --> 00:53:30.330
have to continue working
against that by both marking

00:53:30.330 --> 00:53:33.680
all these invisible
terms of dominance,

00:53:33.680 --> 00:53:37.440
like masculinity and whiteness,
whenever we can and just do

00:53:37.440 --> 00:53:42.520
that together as collectively
and systematically as possible.

00:53:42.520 --> 00:53:43.100
-Thank you.

00:53:43.100 --> 00:53:45.346
Next question.

00:53:45.346 --> 00:53:47.470
Please tell us who you are
and frame your question.

00:53:47.470 --> 00:53:48.050
-Hi.

00:53:48.050 --> 00:53:49.446
My name is Sally.

00:53:49.446 --> 00:53:52.580
I'm a student at Bridgewater
State University.

00:53:52.580 --> 00:53:55.080
And I'm doing a project
on discrimination

00:53:55.080 --> 00:53:57.180
against female producers.

00:53:57.180 --> 00:53:59.320
And my question is
to Liza Johnson.

00:54:02.210 --> 00:54:05.260
What are your thoughts
on discrimination

00:54:05.260 --> 00:54:08.750
against female directors
in major film industries?

00:54:08.750 --> 00:54:13.265
And what advice would you give
to upcoming female producers

00:54:13.265 --> 00:54:18.300
or aspiring female producers?

00:54:18.300 --> 00:54:20.325
-And can I ask
you, are you asking

00:54:20.325 --> 00:54:22.700
me to make a distinction
between directors and producers?

00:54:22.700 --> 00:54:24.670
Are you speaking
more collectively

00:54:24.670 --> 00:54:30.530
about women who do executive
upper level jobs in filmmaking?

00:54:30.530 --> 00:54:34.781
-I'm going to say females
who are in the film studios.

00:54:34.781 --> 00:54:35.280
-OK.

00:54:35.280 --> 00:54:37.970
Yeah.

00:54:37.970 --> 00:54:41.980
Well, I think there's
interesting new data that I

00:54:41.980 --> 00:54:43.230
would like to know more about.

00:54:43.230 --> 00:54:45.590
Other people here might
know more than I do.

00:54:45.590 --> 00:54:48.560
But I think the data
has been very clear

00:54:48.560 --> 00:54:54.450
that hiring practices in
film companies, studios,

00:54:54.450 --> 00:55:01.470
and independent projects are
systematically not weighted

00:55:01.470 --> 00:55:04.180
in favor of women
or people of color.

00:55:04.180 --> 00:55:08.150
And I think that's kind of
just proven by the data.

00:55:08.150 --> 00:55:12.320
So my opinion about it
is not that important.

00:55:12.320 --> 00:55:17.050
When it is encountered, I think
it is mostly unconscious, which

00:55:17.050 --> 00:55:19.302
doesn't make it unsystematic.

00:55:19.302 --> 00:55:21.760
But I've never had an experience
where there's a Lex Luthor

00:55:21.760 --> 00:55:23.634
figure being like, I
don't know, little lady,

00:55:23.634 --> 00:55:27.110
I don't think you can do this.

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:31.230
So in the absence of an
evil villain character

00:55:31.230 --> 00:55:34.930
implementing racist
and sexist practices,

00:55:34.930 --> 00:55:36.660
it doesn't mean that
they don't exist.

00:55:36.660 --> 00:55:37.630
They clearly do.

00:55:37.630 --> 00:55:40.280
And I think that I
don't really know

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:41.900
what to do about it
besides all of us

00:55:41.900 --> 00:55:43.670
just keep working
as hard as we can

00:55:43.670 --> 00:55:47.040
and maybe take an interest
in the work that's being done

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:50.954
by the EEOC and by the ACLU.

00:55:50.954 --> 00:55:53.370
-Same question for Christine
and Mary in their own fields.

00:55:56.440 --> 00:55:59.870
-So what would be the corollary
in my field, a discrimination

00:55:59.870 --> 00:56:02.510
against women
candidates or women

00:56:02.510 --> 00:56:05.830
-Women consultants who manage
campaigns and do polling.

00:56:05.830 --> 00:56:06.700
-Yeah.

00:56:06.700 --> 00:56:08.410
-Run firms.

00:56:08.410 --> 00:56:10.300
-We've talked about this.

00:56:10.300 --> 00:56:12.510
It's still an old boys' network.

00:56:12.510 --> 00:56:15.530
And one of my companies
is called Burning Glass

00:56:15.530 --> 00:56:16.640
Consulting.

00:56:16.640 --> 00:56:18.160
I have two female partners.

00:56:18.160 --> 00:56:20.730
We have only female employees.

00:56:20.730 --> 00:56:25.770
And the idea is that
in an all-female firm

00:56:25.770 --> 00:56:29.110
different things are seen,
different perspectives

00:56:29.110 --> 00:56:29.900
are given.

00:56:29.900 --> 00:56:33.820
And too often there's
not a woman at the table.

00:56:33.820 --> 00:56:39.849
And what men think
is-- for example,

00:56:39.849 --> 00:56:41.390
this happens not
only in advertising,

00:56:41.390 --> 00:56:42.680
but in political campaigns.

00:56:42.680 --> 00:56:46.140
So if you got a bunch of male
consultants around the table

00:56:46.140 --> 00:56:49.760
and they're imagining, how
do we reach women voters?

00:56:49.760 --> 00:56:52.510
So they put them in the kitchen.

00:56:52.510 --> 00:56:55.310
And this happens on
both sides of the aisle.

00:56:55.310 --> 00:57:00.380
This was something we tested in
some panel research that I did.

00:57:00.380 --> 00:57:02.922
So the idea from the men is the
women are going to sit around

00:57:02.922 --> 00:57:04.421
the table in the
kitchen and they're

00:57:04.421 --> 00:57:06.570
going to talk about the
political candidate.

00:57:06.570 --> 00:57:10.050
And every woman just
really reacted strongly.

00:57:10.050 --> 00:57:12.860
Like, really, that's how
they're imagining us?

00:57:12.860 --> 00:57:13.896
In the kitchen?

00:57:13.896 --> 00:57:15.270
And that's the
kind of thing that

00:57:15.270 --> 00:57:17.345
happens when there aren't
women at the table.

00:57:20.590 --> 00:57:23.430
It's still kind of tough.

00:57:23.430 --> 00:57:25.230
I don't know that
I can say, oh, I've

00:57:25.230 --> 00:57:27.120
seen so much overt
discrimination.

00:57:27.120 --> 00:57:31.570
I think it's maybe we're
just not thought of

00:57:31.570 --> 00:57:34.915
to be included or
brought to the table.

00:57:34.915 --> 00:57:36.290
And the other
thing that happens,

00:57:36.290 --> 00:57:41.520
honestly, is when you have
a family and you have kids,

00:57:41.520 --> 00:57:44.780
it becomes difficult with all
the demands that are made.

00:57:44.780 --> 00:57:49.100
And so a lot of women I think
opt out at a certain point

00:57:49.100 --> 00:57:52.500
and singularly focus
not very balanced.

00:57:52.500 --> 00:57:53.666
Men continue.

00:57:53.666 --> 00:57:54.166
-Mary?

00:57:56.970 --> 00:57:59.150
-I guess the advice I would
give you-- is it there?

00:57:59.150 --> 00:58:01.160
Yes, it is.

00:58:01.160 --> 00:58:02.380
You need to be resilient.

00:58:02.380 --> 00:58:04.250
You need to be thick-skinned.

00:58:04.250 --> 00:58:07.450
And yes, we do work harder
than our male counterparts.

00:58:07.450 --> 00:58:08.947
And that's still there.

00:58:08.947 --> 00:58:09.780
I wouldn't trade it.

00:58:09.780 --> 00:58:11.410
I still love the
career that I've had.

00:58:11.410 --> 00:58:12.493
And I'm still enjoying it.

00:58:12.493 --> 00:58:13.950
I'm surprised I'm still there.

00:58:13.950 --> 00:58:16.620
I've been there 30 plus years.

00:58:16.620 --> 00:58:19.720
Yeah, you can do it,
but it's not easy.

00:58:19.720 --> 00:58:21.940
Find a mentor, someone who
knows what they're doing.

00:58:21.940 --> 00:58:22.940
They'll put you through.

00:58:22.940 --> 00:58:24.650
There are a lot more
female mentors now

00:58:24.650 --> 00:58:25.608
than there were before.

00:58:25.608 --> 00:58:27.510
I had a male mentor.

00:58:27.510 --> 00:58:28.100
Don't give up.

00:58:30.770 --> 00:58:31.500
-Next question.

00:58:31.500 --> 00:58:33.750
Please frame it to a specific
individual on the panel.

00:58:33.750 --> 00:58:34.520
-Sure.

00:58:34.520 --> 00:58:35.260
Good afternoon.

00:58:35.260 --> 00:58:36.550
My name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:58:36.550 --> 00:58:40.250
I actually come from the
world of social justice

00:58:40.250 --> 00:58:41.060
practitioners.

00:58:41.060 --> 00:58:44.210
I had Transition House, which
is Cambridge's domestic violence

00:58:44.210 --> 00:58:45.950
agency.

00:58:45.950 --> 00:58:48.090
I come here actually
to figure out

00:58:48.090 --> 00:58:53.880
where my work sits between
research and social justice

00:58:53.880 --> 00:58:58.720
and other kinds of
corporate information

00:58:58.720 --> 00:59:00.980
and popular culture.

00:59:00.980 --> 00:59:03.430
And my question is
informed by something

00:59:03.430 --> 00:59:06.080
that Mary said in
her discussion, which

00:59:06.080 --> 00:59:10.400
was informing her colleagues
to talk at the experience

00:59:10.400 --> 00:59:12.430
not the gender.

00:59:12.430 --> 00:59:14.585
But what about when the
experience is gender?

00:59:17.350 --> 00:59:18.060
-Interesting.

00:59:18.060 --> 00:59:20.710
I have to say I wouldn't
have experienced--

00:59:20.710 --> 00:59:23.060
because we market stuff.

00:59:23.060 --> 00:59:24.180
We market products.

00:59:24.180 --> 00:59:29.700
So I haven't had experience with
marketing gender on its own.

00:59:29.700 --> 00:59:32.360
There's always a link to a
product, a service, an idea.

00:59:32.360 --> 00:59:34.510
I guess the closest thing
I would have is maybe

00:59:34.510 --> 00:59:37.290
our campaign for violence
against women, when

00:59:37.290 --> 00:59:38.630
we had to speak out about that.

00:59:38.630 --> 00:59:43.650
And it still was, what's the
experience of the victim?

00:59:43.650 --> 00:59:45.565
And we've had male
victims who were

00:59:45.565 --> 00:59:48.330
a subject of domestic
violence, as well as women.

00:59:48.330 --> 00:59:50.580
Understand the experience
from their point of view.

00:59:50.580 --> 00:59:52.860
How do they want to
be portrayed in this?

00:59:52.860 --> 00:59:56.710
Never mind if we had an idea
that would make more money

00:59:56.710 --> 00:59:57.920
or get more people aware.

00:59:57.920 --> 00:59:59.850
If it disrespects
them or if it makes

00:59:59.850 --> 01:00:01.990
them feel ashamed or
humiliated, it's not worth it.

01:00:01.990 --> 01:00:06.180
So it'd still go back to
understand that core story

01:00:06.180 --> 01:00:07.710
of the individual
that we're trying

01:00:07.710 --> 01:00:11.110
to either talk about or
portray what the experience is

01:00:11.110 --> 01:00:12.130
of being a victim.

01:00:12.130 --> 01:00:14.300
So whether it's a scotch
drinker, et cetera,

01:00:14.300 --> 01:00:15.622
the process is the same.

01:00:15.622 --> 01:00:17.580
But I haven't had that
much experience with it,

01:00:17.580 --> 01:00:18.260
unfortunately.

01:00:18.260 --> 01:00:19.780
Not yet.

01:00:19.780 --> 01:00:22.490
-And with apologies to those who
will have unanswered questions,

01:00:22.490 --> 01:00:24.115
this will have to be
the last question.

01:00:26.060 --> 01:00:26.560
-Hi.

01:00:26.560 --> 01:00:27.226
I'm [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:27.226 --> 01:00:30.100
Coincidentally, I also worked at
another local domestic violence

01:00:30.100 --> 01:00:32.150
services agency,
[INAUDIBLE], which

01:00:32.150 --> 01:00:34.550
works with Transition House.

01:00:34.550 --> 01:00:36.944
And I'm actually in
development and communications,

01:00:36.944 --> 01:00:38.610
but my question's not
really about that.

01:00:38.610 --> 01:00:42.407
It's a much more general
question for Christine,

01:00:42.407 --> 01:00:43.990
specifically, but I
think anyone might

01:00:43.990 --> 01:00:47.180
be able to speak to it, which
is, as a young woman, one

01:00:47.180 --> 01:00:50.290
of my big pet peeves is hearing
a lot about these terrible ways

01:00:50.290 --> 01:00:54.019
that young women talk, like
upspeak or vocal fry and so on.

01:00:54.019 --> 01:00:56.560
And the interesting thing about
that is that I'm getting that

01:00:56.560 --> 01:00:59.040
not only from people who are
clearly speaking in bad faith,

01:00:59.040 --> 01:01:02.050
but also older female relatives
who very much would describe

01:01:02.050 --> 01:01:05.670
themselves as feminists and
think that women my age need

01:01:05.670 --> 01:01:08.110
to change the way we present
ourselves or talk in order

01:01:08.110 --> 01:01:10.651
to be taken seriously and that
we're disadvantaging ourselves

01:01:10.651 --> 01:01:11.260
if we don't.

01:01:11.260 --> 01:01:15.034
So my question is about, how
do you navigate the sense

01:01:15.034 --> 01:01:16.700
that you should be
listened to no matter

01:01:16.700 --> 01:01:19.070
what because what you
have to say is important

01:01:19.070 --> 01:01:20.760
and you shouldn't
be looked down upon

01:01:20.760 --> 01:01:23.442
for being a woman with
the pragmatic need

01:01:23.442 --> 01:01:24.900
to present yourself
in certain ways

01:01:24.900 --> 01:01:26.200
in order to be more effective?

01:01:26.200 --> 01:01:27.616
And this is both
something that we

01:01:27.616 --> 01:01:30.930
face as women in professional
life, as normal people,

01:01:30.930 --> 01:01:33.100
and also candidates
face, I'm sure.

01:01:33.100 --> 01:01:33.600
-Mm-hm.

01:01:33.600 --> 01:01:34.100
Thank you.

01:01:34.100 --> 01:01:35.420
Christine?

01:01:35.420 --> 01:01:38.230
-Let me just ask a question.

01:01:38.230 --> 01:01:41.890
As a young woman, has
anybody ever said--

01:01:41.890 --> 01:01:44.130
and I'm not detecting
this with you

01:01:44.130 --> 01:01:49.444
at all-- that you have
an upspeak or vocal fry

01:01:49.444 --> 01:01:50.360
or anything like that?

01:01:50.360 --> 01:01:52.460
Has that been said
to you personally?

01:01:52.460 --> 01:01:52.970
-Yes.

01:01:52.970 --> 01:01:55.154
Yeah.

01:01:55.154 --> 01:01:56.320
-What was your view of that?

01:01:56.320 --> 01:01:59.840
For example, did it feel like
something constructive and it's

01:01:59.840 --> 01:02:00.559
good to know?

01:02:00.559 --> 01:02:02.600
Or did it feel like
criticism and there's nothing

01:02:02.600 --> 01:02:03.830
you could do about it?

01:02:03.830 --> 01:02:06.210
I'm asking this for a reason
because I have noticed

01:02:06.210 --> 01:02:08.350
with younger women the upspeak.

01:02:08.350 --> 01:02:09.630
I haven't noticed vocal fry.

01:02:09.630 --> 01:02:12.910
This is something new to me
that I've heard just here.

01:02:12.910 --> 01:02:15.000
But I have definitely
noticed the upspeak.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:18.540
And I have actually wondered
about saying something

01:02:18.540 --> 01:02:23.360
as a mentor or a colleague,
because I feel like not only

01:02:23.360 --> 01:02:26.170
do older women notice it and
maybe don't take it seriously,

01:02:26.170 --> 01:02:30.772
but particularly men,
particularly upspeak.

01:02:30.772 --> 01:02:32.230
And I'm just curious
to know what's

01:02:32.230 --> 01:02:37.040
the most constructive
way if somebody like me,

01:02:37.040 --> 01:02:38.590
for example, should notice that?

01:02:38.590 --> 01:02:40.030
What do you think?

01:02:40.030 --> 01:02:42.250
-So I think this
is hard to answer

01:02:42.250 --> 01:02:45.080
because the context in which
it was said to me, actually,

01:02:45.080 --> 01:02:48.270
was by my mother, having
casual conversations with her.

01:02:48.270 --> 01:02:50.940
And of course we all
code switch in the way

01:02:50.940 --> 01:02:52.410
we talk in different
circumstances.

01:02:52.410 --> 01:02:53.993
And at work, I talk
differently than I

01:02:53.993 --> 01:02:56.511
talk to my mom or my friends.

01:02:56.511 --> 01:02:58.510
And I'll probably use
more upspeak and vocal fry

01:02:58.510 --> 01:03:00.990
in more casual contexts.

01:03:00.990 --> 01:03:03.380
Not on purpose, but
that's just what happens.

01:03:03.380 --> 01:03:06.530
So I think that if you're asked
to give feedback on the way

01:03:06.530 --> 01:03:09.120
someone talks or presents
themselves, it's always useful.

01:03:09.120 --> 01:03:12.560
And also if it's couched
in terms of there's nothing

01:03:12.560 --> 01:03:14.460
inherently wrong with
this way of speaking,

01:03:14.460 --> 01:03:18.576
but people are jerks and
they're going to judge you.

01:03:18.576 --> 01:03:20.200
And this is the way
you navigate within

01:03:20.200 --> 01:03:21.781
those oppressive systems.

01:03:21.781 --> 01:03:22.280
-Nice.

01:03:22.280 --> 01:03:23.039
Good for you.

01:03:23.039 --> 01:03:24.580
-I don't know if
that's overly harsh,

01:03:24.580 --> 01:03:27.060
but I always found it's
really frustrating when people

01:03:27.060 --> 01:03:28.991
are judged for the
style of their speech

01:03:28.991 --> 01:03:29.990
rather than the content.

01:03:29.990 --> 01:03:31.656
And it happens more
to oppressed people.

01:03:34.210 --> 01:03:35.676
-I think of so
many comments that

01:03:35.676 --> 01:03:37.050
were made to me
as a young woman,

01:03:37.050 --> 01:03:39.540
both from men and
women, particularly men.

01:03:39.540 --> 01:03:41.970
And I remember, for example,
going to one meeting

01:03:41.970 --> 01:03:43.500
with my male boss.

01:03:43.500 --> 01:03:46.020
And I had a title.

01:03:46.020 --> 01:03:47.510
I was a research person.

01:03:47.510 --> 01:03:52.494
And I had just a pad of paper
ready to-- he was like, don't

01:03:52.494 --> 01:03:53.660
come in with a pad of paper.

01:03:53.660 --> 01:03:55.490
You're going to look
like a secretary.

01:03:55.490 --> 01:03:58.170
And I was like, what
am I supposed to do?

01:03:58.170 --> 01:03:59.854
I need to write stuff down.

01:03:59.854 --> 01:04:01.180
Hm.

01:04:01.180 --> 01:04:03.220
And it was like it
never occurred to me

01:04:03.220 --> 01:04:05.624
that coming in with
a pad of paper,

01:04:05.624 --> 01:04:08.290
people would perceive me as, the
quote unquote, the "secretary."

01:04:08.290 --> 01:04:09.614
So he told me that.

01:04:09.614 --> 01:04:11.280
And then I started
to think, well, maybe

01:04:11.280 --> 01:04:14.070
I should go out and buy one
of those leather binder things

01:04:14.070 --> 01:04:16.760
and put my paper in it so I
look like I have a portfolio.

01:04:16.760 --> 01:04:19.382
Would that be helpful?

01:04:19.382 --> 01:04:20.840
I mean, I've been
in that situation

01:04:20.840 --> 01:04:24.280
where older people had said
things to me as a young woman,

01:04:24.280 --> 01:04:24.780
too.

01:04:24.780 --> 01:04:27.790
And on some level it
was nice to go, oh,

01:04:27.790 --> 01:04:29.120
this is how this is perceived.

01:04:29.120 --> 01:04:30.000
Weird.

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:33.670
But OK, either I'm going
to play along or I'm not.

01:04:33.670 --> 01:04:37.390
And now that I'm on the other
end and an "older person,"

01:04:37.390 --> 01:04:41.690
it's helpful to know what are
constructive ways, if any,

01:04:41.690 --> 01:04:44.128
to point that out.

01:04:44.128 --> 01:04:46.294
-Please join me in thanking
our distinguished panel.

01:04:46.294 --> 01:04:49.752
